President Obama has nominated Pamela Harris to serve on the United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit. Harris is currently a visiting professor at Georgetown University Law Center and a senior advisor to its Supreme Court Institute. She has previously served as the Principal Deputy Assistant Attorney General of the Office of Legal Policy at the United States Department of Justice. Harris has an impressive educational background, having graduated from Yale College and Yale Law School. She has also worked as a clerk for Judge Harry T. Edwards of the United States Court of Appeals and Justice John Paul Stevens of the Supreme Court. Throughout her career, Harris has focused on appellate and Supreme Court litigation, and she has been involved with various academic institutions, including the University of Pennsylvania Law School and Harvard Law School.